Binary entry point (`src/bin/build_dict.rs`) that compiles `dict.steno` into the two Plover JSON dictionaries shipped to the steno device: `out/plain-ts.json` and `out/smart-ts.json`. Depends on the `steno` lib crate for the actual pipeline — `parse_source` → `expand_dict` → `build_plain_dict`/`build_smart_dict` → `to_json` — this file is just orchestration, I/O, and error reporting.

Key behavior: both dictionaries are built and collision-checked *before either file is written* — `guard()` is called for "plain" then "smart", and if either has stroke collisions, `run()` returns `Err` and `write_dict` is never called for either file, so a bad build never leaves a stale-plus-fresh mismatched pair on disk. Collisions are deduplicated via `BTreeSet` before being reported, so the same colliding stroke listed multiple times in `collisions` prints once.

`root()` resolves the workspace root as `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..` — this file assumes it lives at `crates/steno/src/bin/`, two directories below the workspace root where `dict.steno` and `out/` live; moving this crate breaks that relative path. `load_typed()` calls `expand_dict(&entries, None)` — the `None` means no scoping/profile filter is applied at expansion time, so both profiles are later derived from the same fully-expanded `Vec<TypedEntry>` by `build_plain_dict`/`build_smart_dict`.

Final combined byte count (`plain_bytes + smart_bytes`) is printed explicitly because both profiles load together on the device simultaneously, so that sum — not either file alone — is the real size budget to watch.

All error paths return `String` (via `.map_err(|e| e.to_string())`) rather than a typed error, collected up through `run()` into `main`'s `fail()`, which prints to stderr and returns `ExitCode::FAILURE`. No panics on expected failure paths (missing file, parse error, collision) — all are surfaced as `Result::Err`.